, Boubakir Z, Clark SM, Page JE | title = Identification of olivetolic acid cyclase from Cannabis sativa reveals a unique catalytic route to plant polyketides | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 109 | issue = 31 | pages = 12811\u20136 | date = July 2012 | pmid = 22802619 | pmc = 3411943 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.1200330109 }}</ref> This [[polyketide]] is cyclized to [[olivetolic acid]] via [[olivetolic acid cyclase]], and then [[prenylation|prenylated]] with a ten carbon [[isoprenoid]] precursor, [[geranyl pyrophosphate]], using an aromatic prenyltransferase enzyme, [[geranyl-pyrophosphate\u2014olivetolic acid geranyltransferase]], to biosynthesize [[cannabigerolic acid]], which can then be [[decarboxylation|decarboxylated]] to yield cannabigerol.<ref name=Morales2/><ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Fellermeier M, Zenk MH|date=May 1998|title=Prenylation of olivetolate by a hemp transferase yields cannabigerolic acid, the precursor of tetrahydrocannabinol|journal=FEBS Letters|volume=427|issue=2|pages=283\u20135|doi=10.1016/s0014-5793(98)00450-5|pmid=9607329}}<!--|access-date = 2015-05-20--></ref>\n\n== Research ==\n\n{{As of|2019}}, no [[clinical research]] has been conducted to test the specific effects of cannabigerol in humans.<ref name=\"pubchem\">{{cite web |url=https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Cannabigerol |title=Cannabigerol; ID 5315659 |publisher=PubChem, National Library of Medicine, US National Institutes of Health |date=11 May 2019 |access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nCannabigerol is under [[basic research|laboratory research]] to determine its [[pharmacology|pharmacological]] properties and potential effects in disease conditions.<ref name=pubchem/><ref name=\"Morales\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Morales P, Hurst DP, Reggio PH | title = Molecular Targets of the Phytocannabinoids: A Complex Picture | journal = Progress in the Chemistry of Organic Natural Products | volume = 103 | pages = 103\u2013131 | year = 2017 | pmid = 28120232 | pmc = 5345356 | doi = 10.1007/978-3-319-45541-9_4 | isbn = 978-3-319-45539-6 | series = Progress in the Chemistry of Organic Natural Products }}</ref> Contrary to the major [[Psychoactive drug|psychoactive]] cannabinoid [[THC]], cannabigerol antagonizes [[CB1 receptor]]s and is both an [[alpha-adrenergic|alpha2-adrenoceptor agonist]] and moderate [[5HT1A receptor]] antagonist.<ref name=pubchem/><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Cascio MG, Gauson LA, Stevenson LA, Ross RA, Pertwee RG | title = Evidence that the plant cannabinoid cannabigerol is a highly potent alpha2-adrenoceptor agonist and moderately potent 5HT1A receptor antagonist | journal = British Journal of Pharmacology | volume = 159 | issue = 1 | pages = 129\u201341 | date = January 2010 | pmid = 20002104 | pmc = 2823359 | doi = 10.1111/j.1476-5381.2009.00515.x }}</ref> Cannabigerol displays [[Cannabinoid receptor|CB1 and CB2 binding affinity]].<ref name=pubchem/><ref name=Morales/> Additionally, cannabigerol has been evaluated in laboratory models of [[colitis]]<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Couch DG, Maudslay H, Doleman B, Lund JN, O'Sullivan SE | title = The Use of Cannabinoids in Colitis: A Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis | journal = Inflammatory Bowel Diseases | volume = 24 | issue = 4 | pages = 680\u2013697 | date = March 2018 | pmid = 29562280 | doi = 10.1093/ibd/izy014 | url = http://eprints.nottingham.ac.uk/49221/1/IBD-D-17-00866_R1.pdf }}</ref> and  neuroinflammation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pivotalcbd.com/cbg-flower/what-is-cbg/|title=What is CBG?|website=Pivotal CBD, Grown by Nature Proven by Science|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref> in a chronic model of multiple sclerosis\n\n== Legal status ==\n\nCannabigerol is not scheduled by the UN [[Convention on Psychotropic Substances]].{{citation needed|date=April 2018}} In the United States, it is not a controlled substance under the [[Controlled Substances Act]] as long as it is not produced from the controlled parts of the cannabis plant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/USCODE-2016-title21/pdf/USCODE-2016-title21-chap13-subchapI-partA-sec802.pdf|title=USC > Title 21 > Chapter 13 > Subchapter I > Part A > \u00a7 802. Definitions: (16)|date=2016|website=Government Publishing Office - US Code}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Cannabinoid]]\n* [[Medical cannabis]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Cannabinoids}}\n{{Adrenergic receptor modulators}}\n{{Cannabinoid receptor modulators}}\n{{Serotonin receptor modulators}}\n{{Transient receptor potential channel modulators}}\n\n[[Category:Cannabinoids]]\n[[Category:Terpeno-phenolic compounds]]\n[[Category:Resorcinols]]\n[[Category:CB1 receptor antagonists]]\n", "name_user": "Zefr", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce to clarify; Research - rv unreliable spam ref and neuroinflammation comment", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cannabigerol"}
{"title_page": "Showbox", "text_new": "{{For|the music venue in Seattle|The Showbox}}\n{{Expand Korean|\uc1fc\ubc15\uc2a4|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Showbox Corporation\n| logo = SHOWBOX Co., Ltd. (South Korea) logo.png\n| logo_caption = Showbox logo\n| trading_name = \n| native_name = {{infobox name module\n| hangul = ({{linktext|\uc8fc}}){{linktext|\uc1fc|\ubc15\uc2a4}}\n| hanja = ({{linktext|\u682a}})\uc1fc\ubc15\uc2a4\n| rr = (Ju) Syopakseu\n| mr =(Chu) Syopaks\u016d\n}}\n| former_name = Showbox Mediaplex Co., Inc. {{small|(\uc1fc\ubc15\uc2a4 \u321c\ubbf8\ub514\uc5b4\ud50c\ub809\uc2a4)}}\n| type = [[Joint-stock company|Joint-stock]]\n| traded_as = {{Korea Exchange|086980}} {{small|(July 7, 2006)}}\n| ISIN = \n| ISIN2 = \n| industry = Entertainment, media\n| genre = \n| fate = \n| predecessor = Media Flex Co., Ltd.\n| successor = Showbox Co., Ltd.\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1999|6|10}} in [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]]\n| founder = Yoo Jung-hoon\n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| hq_location = [[Nambusunhwan]], [[Gangnam District|Gangnam]]\n| hq_location_city = Seoul\n| hq_location_country = South Korea\n| num_locations = \n| num_locations_year =\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = Yoo Jung-hoon {{small|(CEO & founder)}}\n| products = \n| brands = \n| production = \n| production_year =\n| services = Film distribution\n| revenue = 12,327,000,000 won\n| revenue_year = 2014\n| operating_income = 2,086,000,000 won\n| income_year =\n| net_income = 20000,000 won\n| net_income_year = \n| assets = \n| assets_year = \n| equity = 105,272,000,000 won\n| equity_year = 2014\n| owner = {{ubl|[[Orion Holdings]]: 57.50%|Lee Hwa-kyung: 0.3%}}\n| members = \n| members_year =\n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent = \n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| website = {{URL|http://www.showbox.co.kr/}}\n| footnotes = \n| intl = <!-- Set positively (\"true\"/\"yes\"/etc) if company is international, otherwise omit -->\n}}\n\n'''SHOWBOX Co., Ltd.''' ({{Ko-hhrm|(\uc8fc)\uc1fc\ubc15\uc2a4}}) is one of the largest [[Film distributor|film distribution companies]] in [[South Korea]], founded in 1996.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.showbox.co.kr/comp/history.asp |language=Korean |title=ShowBox \ud68c\uc0ac\uc5f0\ud601 |website=www.showbox.co.kr |series=HOME > COMPANY |trans-title=ShowBox History}}</ref> Showbox is the film investment, production and distribution branch of Mediaplex, Inc., entertainment arm of [[Orion Confectionery|Orion Group]]. Its main competitors for domestic box office are [[CJ Entertainment]], [[Lotte Entertainment]], and [[Next Entertainment World]] (NEW). Despite having very short history in the industry, they managed to have top 6 of 10 blockbusters in Korean box office history, number 1 being 2012's ''[[The Thieves]]'' and continues to have a series of hits. and also more popular among people\n\n== History ==\n* June 1996: Establishment of Media Flex Co., Ltd. to enter the movie business.\n* November 1999: Establishment of [[Megabox (movie theaters)|Megabox]] to enter the movie theater business.\n* January 2002: Establishment of ShowBox brand and start of movie distribution investment.\n* December 2002: [[Sex Is Zero]] premiers and becomes the fifth most popular film of 2002; selling 4 million tickets.\n* February 2004: [[Taegukgi (film)|Taegukgi]] premiers and hits a new record of 11.74 million tickets sold.\n* August 2005: [[Welcome to Dongmakgol]] premiers and becomes (at the time) as the fourth highest grossing South Korean film of all time; selling 8 million tickets.\n* July 2006: [[The Host (2006 film)|The Host]] premiers and setting a new record of being (at the time) the [[List of highest-grossing films in South Korea|highest grossing South Korean film of all time]]; selling 13 million tickets\n* July 2007: [[Megabox (movie theaters)|Megabox]] sold to US [[Macquarie Group|Macquarie]] Investment Fund.\n* August 2007:[[D-War]] premiers and setting a new record of being (at the time) the highest-budgeted South Korean film of all time; selling 8.42 million tickets.\n* February 2008: [[The Chaser (2008 film)|The Chaser]] premiers and sells 5 million tickets.\n* July 2009: [[Take Off (2009 film)|Take Off]] premiers and becomes the 2nd most attended film of the year in South Korea; selling 8.39 million tickets.\n* February 2010: [[Secret Reunion]] premiers and becomes one of the highest grossing Korean films of 2010; selling 5.5 million tickets.\n* January 2011: [[Detective K: Secret of the Virtuous Widow]] premiers and becomes the 4th best selling Korean film of 2011; selling 4.78 million tickets.\n* February 2012: [[Nameless Gangster: Rules of the Time]] premiers and sells 4.71 million thousand tickets.\n* July 2012: [[The Thieves]] premiers and becomes (at the time) as the fifth highest-grossing movie in Korean film history; selling 12.9 million tickets.\n* May 2013: [[Secretly, Greatly]] premiers and breaks several box office records in South Korea: the highest single day opening for a domestic film, most tickets sold in one day for a domestic film, the biggest opening weekend, the highest-grossing webtoon-based film, and the fastest movie to reach the million, two million, three million, and four million marks in audience number; selling 4.71 million tickets.<ref name=teen>{{cite web||last=Byun|first=hee-won|title=''Secretly Greatly'' Blazes Trail at Box Office by Tapping Teen Audience|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2013/06/10/2013061001331.html|work=[[The Chosun Ilbo]]|accessdate=June 10, 2013|date=June 10, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Yun|first=Suh-young|title=''Secretly'' success shows teen power at box office|url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/culture/2013/06/141_137220.html|work=[[The Korea Times]]|accessdate=June 19, 2013|date=June 10, 2013}}</ref>\n* September 2013: [[The Face Reader]] premiers and became one of the highest-grossing films in South Korea in 2013; selling 9.1 million tickets.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Hyo-won|title=''The Face Reader'' Shines at South Korea's Dae Jong Film Awards|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/face-reader-shines-at-south-652497|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=November 5, 2013|date=November 1, 2013}}</ref>\n* May 2014: [[A Hard Day]] premiers and sells 3.44 million tickets.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Hard Day (2014)|url=http://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/jsp/films/index/filmsView.jsp?movieCd=20130442|website=Korean Film Biz Zone|accessdate=June 12, 2015}}</ref>\n* February 2015: [[Detective K: Secret of the Lost Island]] premiers and the 9th highest grossing film of 2015; selling 3.87 million tickets.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kim|first1=Hee-eun|title=''Detective K'' team returns to set|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=2990322|website=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|date=June 10, 2014|accessdate=December 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Tae|first1=Sang-joon|title=DETECTIVE K: LABORER'S DAUGHTER to Crankin in June|url=http://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/jsp/news/news.jsp?mode=VIEW&seq=3065|website=Korean Film Biz Zone|accessdate=December 15, 2014|date=June 16, 2014}}</ref>\n* March 2015: entered into an exclusive partnership with one of the biggest Chinese entertainment companies, [[Huayi Brothers]], and expanding its way to China and a co-produced partnership with the [[Hollywood]] genre movie studio [[Blumhouse Productions|Blumhouse]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Hyo-won|title=South Korea's Showbox and China's Huayi Bros. Ink Co-Production Deal|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/south-koreas-showbox-chinas-huayi-784546|accessdate=December 4, 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hand In Hand With China - Korea-Chinese Co-production Creates Global Demand|url=http://www.businesskorea.co.kr/english/news/lifestyle/9801-hand-hand-china-korea-chinese-co-production-creates-global-demand|accessdate=December 4, 2017|work=Business Korea|date=March 26, 2015}}</ref>\n* June 2015: Changed the company names from ''Showbox Mediaplex Co., Inc.'' to ''Showbox Co., Ltd.'', in a step to unify the brand name.\n* March 2019: Showbox entered the [[Korean drama|drama]] production industry. It signed a consignment deal with generalist network [[JTBC]], being the second film company to do so (the first being [[Next Entertainment World|NEW]]).<ref name=\"hankyung\">[https://www.hankyung.com/entertainment/article/201903192100H [\ub2e8\ub3c5] \uc1fc\ubc15\uc2a4 \uccab \ub4dc\ub77c\ub9c8 '\uc774\ud0dc\uc6d0\ud074\ub77c\uc4f0'\u00b7'\ub300\uc138\ub140', JTBC\uc5d0\uc11c \ubcf8\ub2e4]</ref>\n\n==Releases==\n===Films===\n{{See also|Category:Showbox films}}\n{{hidden begin\n\n|showhide = \n|title = Click on the 'Show' button to view this table\n|titlestyle= background:Gainsboro  \n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! width=100|Production Country\n! Release date{{efn|Release date in South Korea}}\n! Production type\n! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2002\n| ''[[Addicted (2002 film)|Addicted]]''\n| rowspan=\"4\"|[[South Korea]]\n| October 25, 2002\n| rowspan=\"30\"|[[Live action]]\n| rowspan=\"6\"|[[Film distribution|Distribution]]{{efn|In South Korea}}\n|-\n| ''[[Sex Is Zero]]''\n| December 12, 2002\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\"|2003\n| ''[[Double Agent (2003 film)|Double Agent]]''\n| January 24, 2003\n|-\n| ''[[Garden of Heaven]]''\n| April 4, 2003\n|-\n| ''[[Adaptation (film)|Adaptation]]''\n| [[United States]]\n| May 5, 2003\n|-\n| ''[[Oh Brothers]]''\n| South Korea\n| September 5, 2003\n|-\n| ''[[Underworld (2003 film)|Underworld]]''\n| United States\n| September 26, 2003\n| {{ubl|Import|Distribution}}\n|-\n| ''[[Silver Knife]]''\n| rowspan=\"5\"|South Korea\n| October 24, 2003\n| rowspan=\"3\"|Distribution\n|-\n| ''[[North Korean Guys]]''\n| December 31, 2003\n|-\n| rowspan=\"19\"|2004\n| ''[[Ice Rain (film)|Ice Rain]]''\n| January 16, 2004\n|-\n| ''[[Spy Girl]]''\n| January 30, 2004\n| rowspan=\"2\"|Provider\n|-\n| ''[[Taegukgi (film)|Taegukgi]]''\n| February 5, 2004\n|-\n| ''[[The Human Stain]]''\n| United States\n| March 3, 2004\n| {{ubl|Import|Distribution}}\n|-\n| ''[[Dance with Solitude]]''\n| rowspan=\"4\"|South Korea\n| March 19, 2004\n| rowspan=\"4\"|Distribution\n|-\n| ''[[The Last Wolf]]''\n| April 4, 2004\n|-\n| ''[[The Big Swindle]]''\n| April 15, 2004\n|-\n| ''[[The President's Barber]]''\n| May 5, 2004\n|-\n| ''[[Ong-Bak: Muay Thai Warrior]]''\n| [[Thailand]]\n| May 26, 2004\n| {{ubl|Import|Distribution}}\n|-\n| ''[[Dead Friend]]''\n| South Korea\n| June 17, 2004\n| Distribution\n|-\n| ''[[One Missed Call (2003 film)|One Missed Call]]''\n| [[Japan]]\n| September 7, 2004\n| {{ubl|Import|Distribution}}\n|-\n| ''[[Temptation of Wolves]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|South Korea\n| July 22, 2004\n| rowspan=\"2\"|Distribution\n|-\n| ''[[Sisil-li 2 kilometer]]''\n| August 13, 2004\n|-\n| ''[[Around the World in 80 Days (2004 film)]]''\n| United States\n| September 17, 2004\n| {{ubl|Import|Distribution}}\n|-\n| ''[[Crying Out Love in the Center of the World]]''\n| Japan\n| October 10, 2004\n| Distribution\n|-\n| ''[[The Scarlet Letter (2004 film)|The Scarlet Letter]]''\n| South Korea\n| October 29, 2004\n| Provider\n|-\n| ''[[The Butterfly Effect]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|United States\n| November 12, 2004\n| Distribution\n|-\n| ''[[Blade: Trinity]]''\n| December 15, 2004\n| {{ubl|Import|Distribution}}\n|-\n| ''[[Shinsukki Blues]]''\n| South korea\n| December 30, 2004\n| Provider\n|-\n|}\n\n{{Hidden end}}\n\n===Television series===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Original title\n! Network\n! Associated production\n! Ref.\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Itaewon Class]]''\n| \uc774\ud0dc\uc6d0 \ud074\ub77c\uc4f0\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[JTBC]]\n| Zium Content<br>Itaewon Class Production Partners\n| <ref name=\"hankyung\" /><ref>[http://star.mt.co.kr/stview.php?no=2019071809422098116&MS1 \ubc15\uc11c\uc900X\uae40\ub2e4\ubbf8X\uc720\uc